Daniel Nicholls, 34, from Notting Hill, west London, appeared at Westminster Magistrates’ Court yesterday where he pleaded guilty to one count of trespassing at the palace on January 27 this year. He was fined £100 with costs of £84 and a surcharge to fund victim services of £34. The Metropolitan Police said Nicholls had scaled a perimiter fence before being detained. A spokesman said: “At around 12:40am police detained a 34-year-old man after he breached the boundary fence at The Royal Mews. “He was found by officers having climbed back to the public road and was arrested for trespass on a protected site.”